SIMPLE: calliope
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Calliope
<hw>Cal*li"o*pe</hw> <pr>(k⟦acr⟧l*l⟦imac⟧"⟦osl⟧*p⟦esl⟧)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>Calliope</ets>, Gr. <grk>Kallio`ph</grk>,
lit, the beautiful-voiced; pref. <grk>kalli-</grk> (from
<grk>kalo`s</grk> beautiful) + <grk>'o`ps</grk>, <grk>'opo`s</grk>,
voice.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Class. Myth.)</fld> <def>The Muse that
presides over eloquence and heroic poetry; mother of Orpheus, and chief
of the nine Muses.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>One of the asteroids. See
<er>Solar</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A musical instrument consisting of a series of steam
whistles, toned to the notes of the scale, and played by keys arranged
like those of an organ. It is sometimes attached to steamboat
boilers.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A beautiful species of humming
bird (<spn>Stellula Calliope</spn>) of California and adjacent
regions.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Calliophis</ent>⟦br⟧
